<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[840,1479,1041,1956]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Application of the name 
<taxonomicName box="[1103,1195,1152,1174]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanum">
<emphasis box="[1103,1195,1152,1174]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. incanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been incredibly confused and variable since its first description. This could be grounds for its rejection (see 
<taxonomicName box="[975,1095,1208,1230]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linnaeanum">
<emphasis box="[975,1095,1208,1230]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. linnaeanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
below), but we feel its common use to describe eggplant relatives merits its re-circumscription and careful re-use in a more restricted context than previously (e.g., [
<bibRefCitation author="Lester RN &amp; Hazan SMZ" box="[1386,1414,1264,1286]" editor="Hawkes JG &amp; Lester RN &amp; Nee M &amp; Estrada N" journalOrPublisher="Kew: Royal Botanic Gardens Kew" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="369 - 387" refId="ref10927" refString="29. Lester RN, Hazan SMZ (1991) Origin and domestication of the brinjal eggplant, Solanum melongena, from Solanum incanum, in Africa and Asia. In: Hawkes JG, Lester RN, Nee M, Estrada N, editors. Solanaceae III: taxonomy, chemistry and evolution. Kew: Royal Botanic Gardens Kew, 369 - 387." title="Origin and domestication of the brinjal eggplant, Solanum melongena, from Solanum incanum, in Africa and Asia" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Solanaceae III: taxonomy, chemistry and evolution" year="1991">29</bibRefCitation>
]). The type specimen of 
<taxonomicName box="[1020,1116,1292,1314]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanum">
<emphasis box="[1020,1116,1292,1314]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. incanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
chosen by Hepper and Jaeger [
<bibRefCitation author="Hepper FN &amp; Jaeger P-ML" box="[1444,1472,1292,1314]" journalOrPublisher="Kew Bull" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="387 - 391" part="40" refId="ref11482" refString="45. Hepper FN, Jaeger P-ML (1985) The typification of six Linnaean names in Solanum. Kew Bull 40: 387 - 391." title="The typification of six Linnaean names in Solanum" type="journal article" year="1985">45</bibRefCitation>
] matches material from the Middle East in being densely yellow pubescent with shallowly lobed leaves. Due in part to the misapplication of the name 
<taxonomicName box="[1133,1232,1375,1397]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanum">
<emphasis box="[1133,1232,1375,1397]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. incanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to material from India and southeast Asia and confusion over the differences between 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. incanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[964,1059,1432,1453]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="insanum">
<emphasis box="[964,1059,1432,1453]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. insanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, North African specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[1355,1450,1432,1453]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanum">
<emphasis box="[1355,1450,1432,1453]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. incanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as defined here were often identified and sometimes named as varieties of 
<taxonomicName authority="Forssk." authorityName="Forssk." box="[951,1131,1487,1510]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="coagulans">
<emphasis box="[951,1053,1487,1508]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. coagulans</emphasis>
Forssk.
</taxonomicName>
, an unrelated North African species that can easily be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName box="[1226,1323,1515,1536]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanum">
<emphasis box="[1226,1323,1515,1536]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. incanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its fragrant zygomorphic flowers and berry enclosed in an accrescent calyx; see complete synonymy in [
<bibRefCitation author="Vorontsova MS &amp; Knapp S" box="[1103,1132,1571,1593]" editor="Beentje H" journalOrPublisher="Richmond: RBG Kew" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="164 - 186" refId="ref10772" refString="25. Vorontsova MS, Knapp S (2012) Solanum sections Oliganthes, Melongena and Monodolichopus. In: Edmonds JM, Solanaceae, In: Beentje H, editor. Flora of Tropical East Africa. Richmond: RBG Kew, 164 - 186, 198 - 215, 220 - 223." title="Solanum sections Oliganthes, Melongena and Monodolichopus" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Flora of Tropical East Africa" year="2012">25</bibRefCitation>
]. The most common misapplication of the epithet ‘‘incanum’’ is its use to describe any wild eggplant relative from Africa, most commonly 
<taxonomicName box="[1210,1371,1626,1648]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="campylacanthum">
<emphasis box="[1210,1371,1626,1648]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. campylacanthum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[840,1479,1041,1956]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<taxonomicName box="[864,1019,1654,1676]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanum">
<emphasis box="[864,1019,1654,1676]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Solanum incanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1040,1115,1655,1677]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="4.[155,220,172,191]" captionTargetBox="[160,1391,167,1911]" captionTargetId="figure-0@3.[155,1397,162,1916]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. Representative flower and fruit morphology of eggplant and its wild relatives. A. Solanum campylacanthum inflorescences (Kenya - Vorontsova et al. 157); B. Solanum incanum immature fruit (Kenya – Vorontsova et al. 203); C. Solanum insanum fruit cross-section (China – Wang et al. 2047); D. Solanum insanum inflorescence with several hermaphrodite flowers (China – Wang et al. 2039); E. Solanum linnaeanum with yellow mature and mottled green immature fruit, note highly dissected leaves (Spain - Knapp IM-10096); F. Solanum melongena flower with duplicated parts (China – Wang et al. 2042). Photographs: A, B taken M.S. Vorontsova; C, D, E, F taken by S. Knapp. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0057039.g001" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6338574" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6338574/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
) is a species of dry regions from northern Kenya to Pakistan and in general occurs in drier areas than do other species of the group, although all are weedy and occupy a wide variety of habitats. It is morphologically most similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[939,1063,1766,1787]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lichtensteinii">
<emphasis box="[939,1063,1766,1787]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. lichtensteinii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of southern Africa and clustered with that species in phenetic analyses [
<bibRefCitation author="Lester RN &amp; Hazan SMZ" box="[1136,1164,1795,1817]" editor="Hawkes JG &amp; Lester RN &amp; Nee M &amp; Estrada N" journalOrPublisher="Kew: Royal Botanic Gardens Kew" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="369 - 387" refId="ref10927" refString="29. Lester RN, Hazan SMZ (1991) Origin and domestication of the brinjal eggplant, Solanum melongena, from Solanum incanum, in Africa and Asia. In: Hawkes JG, Lester RN, Nee M, Estrada N, editors. Solanaceae III: taxonomy, chemistry and evolution. Kew: Royal Botanic Gardens Kew, 369 - 387." title="Origin and domestication of the brinjal eggplant, Solanum melongena, from Solanum incanum, in Africa and Asia" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Solanaceae III: taxonomy, chemistry and evolution" year="1991">29</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Mace ES &amp; Lester RN &amp; Gebhardt CG" box="[1169,1197,1795,1817]" journalOrPublisher="Theor Appl Genet" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="626 - 633" part="99" refId="ref10993" refString="30. Mace ES, Lester RN, Gebhardt CG (1999) AFLP analysis of genetic relationships among the cultivated eggplant, Solanum melongena L., and wild relatives (Solanaceae). Theor Appl Genet 99: 626 - 633." title="AFLP analysis of genetic relationships among the cultivated eggplant, Solanum melongena L., and wild relatives (Solanaceae)" type="journal article" year="1999">30</bibRefCitation>
]. The species can be easily distinguished by geography and by the young stems on dry specimens that are more deeply ridged in 
<taxonomicName box="[1258,1383,1850,1871]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lichtensteinii">
<emphasis box="[1258,1383,1850,1871]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. lichtensteinii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and only shallowly or not at all ridged in 
<taxonomicName box="[1157,1251,1878,1899]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanum">
<emphasis box="[1157,1251,1878,1899]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. incanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[840,1479,1041,1956]" lastBlockId="8.[155,793,164,523]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Lester and Hasan [
<bibRefCitation author="Lester RN &amp; Hazan SMZ" box="[1052,1080,1906,1928]" editor="Hawkes JG &amp; Lester RN &amp; Nee M &amp; Estrada N" journalOrPublisher="Kew: Royal Botanic Gardens Kew" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="369 - 387" refId="ref10927" refString="29. Lester RN, Hazan SMZ (1991) Origin and domestication of the brinjal eggplant, Solanum melongena, from Solanum incanum, in Africa and Asia. In: Hawkes JG, Lester RN, Nee M, Estrada N, editors. Solanaceae III: taxonomy, chemistry and evolution. Kew: Royal Botanic Gardens Kew, 369 - 387." title="Origin and domestication of the brinjal eggplant, Solanum melongena, from Solanum incanum, in Africa and Asia" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Solanaceae III: taxonomy, chemistry and evolution" year="1991">29</bibRefCitation>
] proposed that their ‘‘ 
<taxonomicName box="[1301,1413,1906,1928]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanum">S. incanum</taxonomicName>
group C’’ (= 
<taxonomicName box="[907,1001,1934,1955]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanum">
<emphasis box="[907,1001,1934,1955]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">S. incanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as defined here) was the ancestral type and that all the rest of the species were derived from it in a bidirectional manner (i.e., 
<taxonomicName box="[288,397,192,214]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="melongena">
<emphasis box="[288,397,192,214]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. melongena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to the east and 
<taxonomicName box="[563,725,192,214]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="campylacanthum">
<emphasis box="[563,725,192,214]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. campylacanthum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to the south, then giving rise to 
<taxonomicName box="[401,525,220,242]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lichtensteinii">
<emphasis box="[401,525,220,242]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. lichtensteinii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
still further to the south); if polyploidy is indeed occuring in this group (see above under 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="campylacanthum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. campylacanthum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) this scenario needs re-examination. Chromosome counts have not been published for material that is verifiably 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. incanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but high fertility in crosses with 
<taxonomicName box="[581,692,332,354]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="melongena">
<emphasis box="[581,692,332,354]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">S. melongena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[
<bibRefCitation author="Daunay M-C &amp; Hazra P" box="[711,738,332,354]" editor="Peter KV &amp; Hazra P" journalOrPublisher="Houston: Studium Press" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="257 - 322" refId="ref10579" refString="19. Daunay M-C, Hazra P (2012) Eggplant. In: Peter KV, Hazra P, editors. Handbook of Vegetables. Houston: Studium Press, 257 - 322." title="Eggplant" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Handbook of Vegetables" year="2012">19</bibRefCitation>
] and molecular work with co-dominant SSR markers [
<bibRefCitation author="Vilanova S &amp; Blasco M &amp; Hurtado M &amp; Munoz-Falcon JE &amp; Prohens J" box="[633,661,360,382]" editor="Prohens J &amp; Rodriguez-Burruezo A" journalOrPublisher="Valencia: Editoral de la Universitat Politecnica de Valencia" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="435 - 439" refId="ref11509" refString="46. Vilanova S, Blasco M, Hurtado M, Munoz-Falcon JE, Prohens J, et al. (2010) Development of a linkage map of eggplant based on a S. incanum x S. melongena backcross generation. In: Prohens J, Rodriguez-Burruezo A, editors. Advances in genetics and breeding of capsicum and eggplant. Valencia: Editoral de la Universitat Politecnica de Valencia, 435 - 439." title="Development of a linkage map of eggplant based on a S. incanum x S. melongena backcross generation" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Advances in genetics and breeding of capsicum and eggplant" year="2010">46</bibRefCitation>
] suggests it is diploid. 
<taxonomicName box="[244,400,388,410]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incanum">
<emphasis box="[244,400,388,410]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Solanum incanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is being used in eggplant breeding programmes as a source of variation for phenolics content and resistance to drought as well as to develop ILs (introgression lines, see [
